description:
In the Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince movie, there is a dispute between Albus Dumbledore and Draco Malfoy over the attempted assassination of Dumbledore.
#Background: Draco Malfoy, a student at Hogwarts School of Witchcraft and Wizardry and a member of the pure-blood Malfoy family, is entrusted with the task of assassinating Dumbledore by Lord Voldemort. Dumbledore becomes aware of the plot and confronts Malfoy, offering him a chance to back out and revealing the true extent of the danger and moral implications of his actions. However, Malfoy ultimately decides to go through with the assassination attempt, leading to a confrontation between Dumbledore and Malfoy.
After considering all the evidence, the jurors would have to decide whether Malfoy was guilty of attempted murder or if he was acting under duress. The Kleros Court's decision would be final and binding, bringing a resolution to the dispute.
Go to the Arbitrable Application
evidence: {'0': {'title': 'draco malfoy should not be found guilty', 'description': "draco malfoy did not have the intent to commit murder but rather was forced or coerced into participating in the assassination plot against albus dumbledore it could be argued that malfoy was under duress or fear of harm to himself or his loved ones if he did not comply with voldemort's orders and therefore his actions should be considered involuntary additionally it could be argued that the background provides little information on the specific details of the confrontation between dumbledore and malfoy and it is not clear if malfoy was able to express his reluctance or if he was still under duress in this view it could be argued that draco malfoy should not be found guilty of attempted murder as his actions were not fully voluntary and he may not have had the intent to kill"}, '1': {'title': 'draco malfoy is guilty of attempted murder in the assassination plot against albus dumbledore', 'description': 'in the given background it is stated that draco malfoy is entrusted with the task of assassinating dumbledore by lord voldemort also it is stated that malfoy ultimately decides to go through with the assassination attempt leading to a confrontation between dumbledore and malfoy it indicates that malfoy had the intention and actively moving towards to commit the murder and as per the legal definition of attempted murder is when a person has intent to kill and takes a direct step towards committing the murder therefore based on the information provided it can be concluded that draco malfoy is guilty of attempted murder in the assassination plot against albus dumbledore'}}

description: Someone requested to add a token to the token curated registry of tokens.
evidence: {'0': {'title': 'my response', 'description': 'the points made by the challenger don’t really apply in this situation 1 the first one “zilliqazil was an erc20 token before its mainnet token launched and so are aeternityae or wanchainwan will we allow tokens in the noneth chain to be listed here due only to project owners expressing an intention to create an ethbased counterpart or only when that token is live on eth mainnet” i don’t see how this point applies to the case in question all the synths have always been only on eth and there have been no token swaps to other chains on top of that we also do allow wrapped versions of noneth tokens to be listed in our case the tokens are already live on mainnet so i don’t see the point 2 on the topic of contract addresses “my stand to reject the listing is also supported by policy line4 on the importance of checking contract addresses there were many listing updates in the past for token contracts that were olddeprecated and replaced with a new listing with the new token contract” this doesn’t apply in our case it would be correct only if we already had a new version of these inverse synths but we don’t the synths submitted are the most recent versions of the token and as such the one that should be listed in the tcr this point can only be valid if and when a new version of these synths is live 3 the challenger also says “have you actually tried swapping any of these submitted frozen inverse synths to other synths i did and none of your submissions can be swapped only ibtc as what the synth monitoring link i sent was about” the challenger is claiming that he tried swapping these inverse synths but was been unable to do so i find that very hard to believe for a few reasons first of all only people that already own the asset could have done the swap as we saw in the previous pieces of evidence the chances of the challenger having some are low but if that was the case i am sure that he could point us to his wallet and transaction where he tried to do these swaps but most importantly if we go by snx documentation the challenger claim is clearly false since you can swap the assets back to other synths or susd even if frozen otherwise what would be the point of such an asset that if the price moves too much you are stuck with it forever and unable to redeem it snx is clear on this and quoting description:
Gitcoin Grant
Rules
Gitcoin grants should only serve funding of public good. See the explanation of public goods in Wikipedia.
All the funding of the grant should go toward the goal stated in the grant.
It is forbidden to impersonate a person or an entity in the grant description.
People giving money to the grant should only do so because they want the public good to be funded. It is forbidden to offer a reward to people funding the grant.
Disputed grant
The disputed grant is the Synergy of Serra
Reason for the dispute
"Every person that donated to this grant has left a comment with the account address where they want the kickback"
Go to the Arbitrable Application

description:
Introduction
Claimant seeks compensation for a discrepancy in PNK rewards (71935.48 PNK) he suffered by the Kleros Cooperative’s incorrect moving away of his two January 2020 storytelling submissions to the second timeframe. Respondent had been notified of the issue less than six hours after its sharing of the reward spreadsheet; yet, it has failed to correct the mistake either at the time or after the fact. After months of discussions and leaving the matter pending, the parties cease such efforts and cause a case to be brought to the Kleros Court.
The Program Terms and Subcourt Jurisdiction
The full information on the previous centralized storytelling program can be found on the Kleros blog, with a 25/02/2020 archive on the Wayback Machine (the "Program Terms"). The Program Terms provided: "In case a participant disagrees with his share of the reward, Kleros Escrow will be used to settle the dispute." A summary version of the Program Terms can be found in a previously used primary document for disputes on rewards.
The parties have agreed to change the resolution mechanism from the Escrow to the Dispute Resolver for such issues and the Marketing Subcourt was previously stipulated for a related case (no. 167). (See Stipulation [transcript of Telegram chat].) The Kleros Coop did not object to using this specific subcourt for this case. (See July Slack chat [emphasis added].)
Therefore, the Claimant submits this Marketing Subcourt has the jurisdiction to resolve this off-chain dispute created through the Dispute Resolver.
Facts
The Claimant incorporates herein the facts present in the list of exhibits, primarily found in the email thread, and directs the jury’s attention to its highlighted contents.
In short: The publication and submission of the two items were both made on the last day available; the first period was between “10/12/2019 and 10/01/2020”, and 12/01/2020 is “at least a week before the distribution date” (originally planned as 20/01/2020). Therefore, those items should have been included within the first timeframe rather than the second. The first timeframe had very few submissions, making rewards higher. With these items' proper inclusion, their 8 points together should have been out of 50 total points, amounting for 16% of 500000 PNK (that is, 80000 PNK). Because of their improper moving away to the second timeframe and non-resolution of claimant's issue when timely raised, 8064.52 PNK were received instead. (See public spreadsheet at items 33 and 40.)
Timeline
All times in this brief are in Claimant’s local time, that is GMT-4 / ET, except as otherwise noted.
On January 12, 2020, shortly before 5:25 PM (the screenshot time), Claimant made a submission of two items via the Google form for the program. (See screenshots of submission, filled out and confirmed.) The Kleros Coop’s spreadsheet shows a timestamp of "12/01/2020 22:24:13" (Kleros Coop's time). (See screenshot of timestamp on spreadsheet shared by Stuart.) This was “at least a week before the distribution date” (originally planned as 20/01/2020). (See Program Terms.)
On February 4, 2020, Damjan of the Kleros Coop posted in the Telegram group: “we changed our dynamic a bit” and asked to “drop all of your submissions directly to myself.”
On February 6, 2020, assuming the previous submission must be made again and out of caution, Claimant dropped his “first submission” (of items dated January 10th, the last publication day for the first timeframe) via Telegram and had Damjan acknowledge receipt thereof. (See screenshot of first Telegram submission.)
On February 25, 2020, at 10:49 AM, Damjan announced the release of a spreadsheet of tentative rewards.
Less than six hours later, at 4:26 PM, Claimant notified Damjan of the issue in question via Telegram. (See screenshot of notification of issue to Damjan and response.)
On February 27, 2020, at 09:20 AM, Damjan responded to get in touch with Stuart. (See ibid.) Notably, Damjan agreed on behalf of the Kleros Coop “we’re covering the initial dispute fees” in the event of a dispute. (See ibid.)
On February 27, 2020, at 6:19 PM, Claimant emailed Stuart. Absent a response, Claimant followed up on March 6, 2020. (See email thread.)
Over those days and months, the Kleros Coop did not cause a dispute to be created before or after the final distribution, or otherwise resolve the issue, despite claimant’s notice within hours from the first spreadsheet release. However, Stuart raised the possibility to maybe "send over some more PNK." (See ibid. at p. 2.) Claimant indicated he would be awaiting such a possible offer. (See ibid. at p. 1.)
On July 27, 2020, the Kleros Coop finally closed the issue as an internal support matter, by deciding “we won’t make you an offer, nor pay for the initial fees for a case.” (See July Slack chat [emphasis added].) This is contrary to Stuart and Damjan’s previous assertions, respectively.
These previous communications were using an earlier figure of 3921.57 PNK that would be rewarded per item, found on a previous speadsheet. The final spreadsheet rewarded 4032.26 PNK in the end. Claimant has been arguing it should have been 40000 PNK for each of the two items.
The issue now comes as a Kleros Court matter.
Related Case
In Kleros Court Case No. 166, the Court resolved a similar issue in Claimant’s favor. The Kleros Coop had rejected an item published on February 11 and submitted on February 12, with the reason as out of timeframe. The publication and submission were both made on the last day available; the second period was between “11/01/2019sic and 11/02/2020”, and 12/02/2020 was “at least a week before the distribution date” (originally planned as 20/02/2020). Had the Kleros Coop forgotten the submission timeframe was a bit longer than the publication deadline?
Because that issue B and the issue A here are the same on acceptance of the time of submission in keeping with the Program Terms (these letters A and B were used to identify the issues in the email thread), Claimant should similarly be awarded the rewards to which he was entitled here.
Claim
Moving the said two items to the correct timeframe would have meant being rewarded 8% each (40000 PNK each) rather than 0.78% each (4032.26 PNK each). The discrepancy is (40000 x 2) - (4032.26 x 2) = 80000 - 8064.52 = 71935.48 PNK, which Claimant requests for enforcement of the Program Terms and compensation.
Per the Kleros Coop’s February 27, 2020 agreement through its representative Damjan to be “covering the initial dispute fees” in the event of a dispute, the Claimant is entitled to recover the 0.30 ETH paid to create this dispute. (See screenshot of notification of issue to Damjan and response.)
Claimant therefore respectfully requests 71935.48 PNK in compensatory damages and 0.30 ETH in initial arbitration costs.
List of Exhibits
July Slack chat [emphasis added]
Screenshots of submission, filled out and confirmed
Screenshot of timestamp on spreadsheet shared by Stuart
Screenshot of first Telegram submission
Screenshot of notification of issue to Damjan and response
Email thread (highlighted)
Go to the Arbitrable Application

description: Someone requested to add a market to Omen Verified Market

Will there be a day with at least 1000 reported Corona death in the US in the first 14 days of July?
According to https://www.statnews.com/feature/coronavirus/covid-19-tracker there were two days with at least 1000 Coronavirus deaths during the first 14 days of July. This can be verified by changing the selection on the left to "United States" from "Worldwide" and changing the "2 Week" reporting to "1 Day". Both July 7th and July 9th had at least 1000 deaths for the United States, which satisfies the market requirement.
Party A claims that StatNews should not be considered a valid source for Coronavirus reporting and that the market should resolve to NO.
Party B claims that StatNews should be considered a valid source for Coronavirus reporting and that the market should resolve to YES.
The market in question does not specify a source, and it is safe to believe that StatNews is fairly reputable as they are both verified on Twitter and were mentioned by the New York Times for their early coronavirus coverage.
Go to the Arbitrable Application

description:
Gitcoin Grant
Rules
Gitcoin grants should only serve funding of public good. See the explanation of public goods in Wikipedia.
All the funding of the grant should go toward the goal stated in the grant.
It is forbidden to impersonate a person or an entity in the grant description.
People giving money to the grant should only do so because they want the public good to be funded. It is forbidden to offer a reward to people funding the grant.
Disputed grant
The disputed grant is the iearn.finance
Reason for the dispute
"not an active project"
Go to the Arbitrable Application

The hotel however refused to refund the $204 booking payment and refused to waive cancellation/no show fee of $174. In the booking, it does state that payments are non-refundable but the customer didn't see the cancellation fee until after she booked it.
The customer contacted Travala but was told that they have no control over booking policies of the property and was advised to wait until there might be a change in policy. The customer insisted that she is legally not allowed to leave her country nor enter Italy at that time and hence insist on getting the refund through Travala at least.
TOS: https://www.travala.com/terms-and-conditions
Go to the Arbitrable Application

A hotel listed in Travala has canceled an already confirmed booking when it found out that the guest came from Syria.
The guest received an email from Travala 5 days prior to the booking date that he will receive a refund of the total booking value but when he inquired of the reason, the support mentioned it’s the hotel’s decision and not Travala and refused to disclose the exact reason of the refusal.
The guest found comments through social media that the hotel has a history of denying service on certain nationalities. The guest contacted the support again to verify the info but received the same answer from Travala.
TOS: https://www.travala.com/terms-and-conditions

description:
A tragedy struck a couple who’s about to get married in May but his fiancée died in a car crash in Feb. He cancelled the arrangements for the wedding and requested refunds from their wedding providers including their booked videographer.
The videographer company however refused to refund the $1,800 non-refundable deposit. After the bereaved fiancé didn’t hear a satisfactory response from the company for months regarding the refund request, he reached out again to them through email and told of a plan to tell the incident to his friends and post it in the social media, which the company nonchalantly ignored.
Not long after, he left them a 1-star review in TheKnot.com that sparked several bad comments from others towards the company. As a response, the videographer company threatened to sue him and the bride’s family for defamation. The review was taken down.
Go to the Arbitrable Application

description:
Purchaser (Party A) has an established contract with Vendor (Party B) to provide specific deliverable milestones on a set schedule to unlock agreed upon payments per milestone. If Vendor misses the deadline or fails to complete the deliverable within the specifications of the contract, Purchaser can withhold payment or terminate the agreement.
There is also a Force Majeure (Act of God) clause that releases the Vendor from milestone deadlines with no penalty if the agreed upon performance is impacted by an "Act of God" (an instance of uncontrollable natural forces in operation).
Vendor is unable to meet Purchaser's deadlines because the COVID19 pandemic shut down Vendor's work. Purchaser argues that the actual forces affecting the work are Man Made in origin- the lockdown was enacted by governments and maybe weren't necessary, and thus the impacted work is not the result of an act of god. Vendor argues that the root cause is the uncontrollable natural force of the COVID19 virus pandemic.
Go to the Arbitrable Application

description:
Tom is thinking of buying a car but prefers a second-hand unit as his budget is not enough. He knows that using a second-hand car is risky considering it’s already used in many years. But he thinks that small problems can be immediately fixed as soon as he notices it. Compared to having a car loan that needs monthly amortization and takes years to finish.
So he dropped by to a car shop selling old cars and saw it selling an old SUV for $5000. Upon checking the unit, the interiors are still in good condition as well as the exterior. The seats, covers, mirrors, and the paint looks brand new. It also has a good speaker for audio and new tires. Tom paid for the car and the shop gave him the documents notarized.
After a few months of using the car, Tom noticed that the car's performance is getting slower. The air conditioner is not as cold as before and the steering wheel is having some issue. He decides to go back to the car shop and demands a repair for free.

description:
Shane is a freelance writer and is observing the situation since the beginning of the outbreak. Looking back at the time when everyone has freedom. Doing a lot of things, struggling with traffic jams to hit deadlines, and quality time is seasonal. With the sudden surge of virus scarcity, everything has turned upside down.
According to an economist, the "new normal" is happening right now. Situations could go worse as time goes by. The market cannot recover easily as the operations of companies cannot go back to normal. As superstitions in the early days say that in the future, the world will fall deep and a new world will rise. It is clear that coronavirus has resulted in a bad economic impact. As the nations are battling with Covid-19, livelihoods and businesses are much affected. Shares in stocks are being sold hoping to save the losses before it goes worse. Commodities and markets crashed. Travel restrictions and lockdowns are everywhere. Everything is happening for the first time in history.
But based on Shane's research, studies show that emerging technologies can resolve the issues of operations today. For instance, the internet is a great tool for communication and engagement. There are other useful technologies as well, such as AI and Blockchain. These technologies are very useful in developing solutions for any application.
However, with the current situation of staying at home for most individuals, as schools as well were being suspended, Shane thinks that there is a high rate of effectivity in using these technologies. And mass adoption can be gained if the people or community is supported by their needs. Resources is limited and not everyone has access to the internet.
Go to the Arbitrable Application

As the pandemic continues, it is getting harder for the community to move like the normal days as the lockdown limits access to places and in going outdoors. Nowadays, E-commerce platforms are rising because of the significant growth in the business. Buying almost everything you need seems to be available online and that it also boosts the market for the logistics industry.
A reliable shopping company in a city offers its online store to serve the community with easy access to groceries and pharmacies by using their platform.
The platform would need the following information to place the orders:
Customer’s Full Name
Complete Address
Eth Address
Total Items
Amount Due
The Challenge
But, there's a "trust issue" with half of the community who are not used to online shopping. As they fear using the platform in sharing private information to shop online.
The Solution
In able to solve this problem, the shopping company would only ask the customers to pay half of the total amount and pay the remaining upon receiving the delivery. So the company looked for a partnership with a reliable delivery company. They made an agreement to collect the customer’s remaining payment on behalf of the latter. They added another payment option which is COD or “Cash On Delivery” for half of the remaining payment.
To take effect, on behalf of the customer the logistics company pays the store owner in advance with 3% off as part of the agreement. And then notifies the customers to prepare the payment ahead of time before the delivery schedule. They can then take the amount collected in every shipment with an extra charge for the delivery fee.
Go to the Arbitrable Application

Jane posted a photo of her restaurant on a social media site to gain more popularity. She really wanted to encourage families and groups of friends to eat in her restaurant.
Dave, on the other hand, posted a negative comment about Jane's restaurant.
"Bad food, horrible service, there's a rat in the kitchen. Don't eat there."
Jane replied to Dave, asking him to message her directly to discuss his complaint so she can do something about it.
She also requested Dave to delete his negative comment, but Dave's reply got the situation even worse.
" Oops, No offense meant. Just my honest opinion."
In less than 40 minutes, that post went viral.
Jane has suffered distress and anxiety because of defamatory content and false statements made by Dave.
According to Jane, social media companies have the capability to censor content, but they won't be able to control how ideas spread offline. Falsehoods and hateful ideas will not spread if people are presented with counter arguments. Jane fights back, demanding the social media platform admin to deactivate Dave's account plus compensation for moral damages.
Go to the Arbitrable Application

When Jane inquired about the return of their security deposit 15 days after they checked out, they were told that they damaged the house and the vacation rental homeowner would be keeping the security deposit. Jane got upset when she heard about the homeowner’s decision.
Jane wanted a full refund of the security deposit so she pointed out a few things to justify her claim:
The faucet handle was already broken when they arrived.
The scratches in the side table were already there when they arrived. They did not damage it.
The wear-and-tear items are very cheap and easy to replace.
The security deposit is too much.
Following are the items that are listed are minor wear-and-tear items and items that were in that condition when they arrived:

Broken tub faucet handle
2 broken cabinet hinges
Scratches in the side table furniture (Master’s bedroom)

description:
Robert has launched a new brand of protein bars and he was looking to promote his protein bars through a prominent fitness influencer on Instagram. He did his research on Instagram & approached multiple influencers. After reaching out to many influencers, Robert finalized Alex for promoting Robert’s new brand of protein bars as Alex seemed to be the most cost-effective option for Robert.
Robert finalized the deal with Alex through verbal communication and they agreed that Robert will keep the agreed amount of 5 ETH in Kleros escrow and Alex would be paid after Alex posts 3 promotional images about Robert’s new brand of protein bars on his Instagram account. However, Robert did not agree to transfer the agreed amount of ETH even after Alex had posted 3 promotional images about Robert’s new brand of protein bars on his Instagram account. Robert believes that the content promoting his products did not garner enough likes & shares as the likes & shares that were received on content promoting his products were comparatively lesser than Alex’s previous posts. On another hand, Alex is saying that there was no communication from his end to assure Robert that the content promoting Robert’s products would receive any minimum number of likes & shares and the only promise made by Alex was to post three promotional images about Robert’s new brand of protein bars.

description:
Introduction
Claimant submits that items 10 through 13 of the “JA KLEROS Storytelling 2020 Submission 2” sheet should be included in the reward spreadsheet rather than omitted. Respondent does not include these items in the second timeframe without giving any reason.
The Program Terms and Subcourt Jurisdiction
The parties stipulated to the use of the attached Primary Document for basic background information on the Kleros Storytelling Reward Program. (See Stipulation.)
The full information on this program can be found on the Kleros blog, with a 25/02/2020 archive on the Wayback Machine (the "Program Terms").
The Program Terms provided: "In case a participant disagrees with his share of the reward, Kleros Escrow will be used to settle the dispute." The parties now stipulated to refer the controversy to this subcourt via the Dispute Resolver by Kleros. (See id.)
The Submission Items' Eligibility
The Program Terms provided: "The second half of the rewards will be distributed on 20/02/2020 for contributions made during the period between 11/01/2019 (sic) and 11/02/2020." Further, participants had to let Respondent "know at least a week before the distribution date" they had their story told. (See Program Terms.)
The items were submitted on 12/02/2020. (See Exhibit A - 12/02/2020 Damjan Telegram Submission 2 and Exhibit B - JA KLEROS Storytelling 2020 Submission 2 (add .xlsx to open).) The links to the items reflect a publication date of 11/02/2020. (See item 10, item 11, item 12 and item 13.) Therefore, the publication and submission were both made on the last day available; the second period was between “11/01/2019 (sic) and 11/02/2020”, and 12/02/2020 is “at least a week before the distribution date” (originally planned as 20/02/2020).
Each of the items comprises of a custom image and copy in Spanish on Kleros' decentralized justice research. They point to a story on the Kleros Fellowship of Justice and the future of decentralized justice research through the "More Information" button. This is in line with the program's purpose of storytelling and comparable to other submissions that were accepted.

Introduction
Claimant submits that submission item 39 of the Kleros Storytelling Rewards sheet should be included within the second timeframe rather than rejected, because it was published on February 11 and submitted on February 12, which would be timely. Respondent rejects this submission item with the reason "out of timeframe."
The Program Terms and Subcourt Jurisdiction
The parties stipulated to the use of the attached Primary Document for basic background information on the Kleros Storytelling Reward Program. (See Stipulation.)
The full information on this program can be found on the Kleros blog, with a 25/02/2020 archive on the Wayback Machine (the "Program Terms").
The Program Terms provided: "In case a participant disagrees with his share of the reward, Kleros Escrow will be used to settle the dispute." The parties now stipulated to refer the controversy to this subcourt via the Dispute Resolver by Kleros. (See id.)
The Submission Item's Timeliness
The Program Terms provided: "The second half of the rewards will be distributed on 20/02/2020 for contributions made during the period between 11/01/2019 (sic) and 11/02/2020." Further, participants had to let Respondent "know at least a week before the distribution date" they had their story told. (See Program Terms.)
The item link reflects a publication date of 11/02/2020. (See Extension des bourses avec des salles intellectuelles de justice — Partie I.) The item was submitted on 12/02/2020. (See Exhibit A - 12/02/2020 Damjan Telegram Submission 2.) Therefore, the publication and submission were both made on the last day available; the second period was between “11/01/2019 (sic) and 11/02/2020”, and 12/02/2020 is “at least a week before the distribution date” (originally planned as 20/02/2020).
